03644nam a22005175i 9780822382249DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19891990ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223822497 a10.1515/97808223822492doi  a(DE-B1597)552414  a(OCoLC)1055128703  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aJC153.L87bD86 1990 7aPOL0000002bisacsh1 aDworetz, Steven M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Unvarnished Doctrine :bLocke, Liberalism, and the American Revolution /cSteven M. Dworetz. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1989] 4cÂ©1990  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the Paperback Edition -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 The Historiographic Revolution: The Rise of "Cato" and the Decline of Locke in American Revolutionary Thought -- t2 A Discourse on Method -- t3 The Lockean Response to British "Innovations" -- t4 Historiography and the Interpretation of Political Theory -- t5 Theistic Liberalism in the Teaching of the New England Clergy -- t6 History, Myth, and the Secular Salvation of American Liberalism -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Unvarnished Doctrine, Steven M. Dworetz addresses two critical issues in contemporary thinking on the American Revolution-the ideological character of this event, and, more specifically, the relevance of "America's Philosopher, the Great Mr. Locke," in this experience. Recent interpretations of the American revolution, particularly those of Bailyn and Pocock, have incorporated an understanding of Locke as the moral apologist of unlimited accumulation and the original ideological crusader for the "spirit of capitalism," a view based largely on the work of theorists Leo Strauss and C. B. Macpherson. Drawing on an examination of sermons and tracts of the New England clergy, Dworetz argues that the colonists themselves did not hold this conception of Locke. Moreover, these ministers found an affinity with the principles of Locke's theistic liberalism and derived a moral justification for revolution from those principles. The connection between Locke and colonial clergy, Dworetz maintains, constitutes a significant, radicalizing force in American revolutionary thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aLiberalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822382249zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822382249423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822382249.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles